               <head>Miscellaneous works on Sufism and poetry, 5 items (a-e)</head>
               <msContents class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008104964 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2006003807 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2010105563">
                  <summary>Miscellaneous collection of works on Sufism, literary criticism and poetry by various authors. Volume not dated; item b dated (17 Jumādá al-Avval 1248/12 October 1832). Nastaʿlīq and shikastah āmīz. Occasional annotations in margins. Stamped foliation. Lacking original binding. Paper dust wrapper (index pages from BEIC legal publication on the Regulations of 1793); no apparent watermarks; labels, torn and stained. Folios unbound; cropped, creased, stains, smudging in parts, wormholes, later repairs. Condition very fragile.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar ur">Persian, Arabic, Urdu</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903D-item1">
                     <locus from="Iv" to="Iv">f. Iv</locus>
                     <textLang mainLang="ur">Urdu</textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 236(a), f. Iv.</p>
                        <p>Untitled Urdu ghazal by a poet identified in the last verse as 
                <persName key="person_f8163" role="aut">Nawshah</persName>, informally scrawled into two columns.
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated at end.</p>
                     </note>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f8163">Nawshah</persName>
                     </author>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903D-item2">
                     <locus from="1v" to="93v">ff. 1v-93v</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 236(b), ff. 1v-93v.</p>
                        <p>Sufi treatise comprising ethically instructive anecdotes and tales in refined prose and poetry and arranged in forty chapters, dedicated to the Timurid Prince 
                <persName key="person_f8164" role="dte">Abū al-Muḥsin</persName>during the reign of his father 
                <persName key="viaf_77382759" role="oth">Abū al-Ghāzī Sulṭān Ḥusayn known as Mīrzā Bāyqarā</persName>, written by one of the leading scholars at court, 
                <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100106528506.0x000001 viaf_90770167" role="aut">Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn Vāʿiẓ Kāshifī Bayhaqī</persName>(d. 910/1505).
                        </p>
                        <p>Dated colophon (f. 93v): completed by 
                <persName key="person_f8165" role="scr">Najaf ʿAlī Riz̤avī Shāhjahānābādī</persName>at qaṣbah Mainpuri (?), 17 Jumādá al-Avval 1248/12 October 1832.
                        </p>
                        <p>Added at the beginning (f. 1r) is an Urdu verse or shiʿr ascribed to 
                <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164657199.0x000001 viaf_37804758">Chandū Laʿl</persName>, Prime Minister of the Āṣaf Jāhī Niẓām al-Mulk and renowned poet of Dakhinī Urdu writing under the takhalluṣ 
                <persName key="viaf_37804758" role="ctb">Shādān</persName>(d. 1259/1843).
                        </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar ur">Persian, Arabic, Urdu</textLang>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_90770167">Ḥusayn al-Kāshifī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" key="viaf_90770167">حسين الكاشفى</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_219">Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_219">اخلاق محسنى</title>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="3" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903D-item3">
                     <locus from="94r" to="102v">ff. 94r-102v</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 236(c), ff. 94r-102v.</p>
                        <p>Untitled commentary on the prose works of 
                <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164657020.0x000001 viaf_30145911203827062840">Ẓuhūrī Turshīzī</persName>(d. 1025/1616) by an unnamed commentator.
                        </p>
                        <p>The text ends abruptly at the end.</p>
                        <p>Not dated at end.</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="4" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903D-item4">
                     <locus from="106r" to="140r">ff. 106r-140r</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 236(d), ff. 106r-140r.</p>
                        <p>Mystical romance set in the Panjāb, inspired by accounts of Laylá and Majnūn, composed in mas̲navī form by 
                <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164656899.0x000001 viaf_242128896">Muḥammad Akram Panjābī “Ghanīmat”</persName>(d. 1100/1698).
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated at end.</p>
                        <p>Shikastah āmīz and nastaʿlīq variously arranged in three to four columns.</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_242128896">Ghanīmat</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" key="viaf_242128896">غنيمت</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21096">Nayrang-i ʿishq</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_21096">نيرنگ عشق</title>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="5" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903D-item5">
                     <locus from="140v" to="142r">ff. 140v-142r</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 236(e), ff. 140v-142r.</p>
                        <p>Untitled collection of miscellaneous Urdu and Persian poems in ghazal form by unidentified poets.</p>
                        <p>Not dated at end.</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="ur" otherLangs="fa">Urdu and Persian</textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
